ce:section.ce:para:
Scheme 3
 illustrates the possible antibacterial mechanisms of CD-1 and CD-2. First, CDs conjugate onto the surface of bacteria through electrostatic adsorption and hydrophobicity. CD-1 is positively charged, and therefore it interacts with bacteria mainly through electrostatic interaction with the negatively charged bacterial cell surface, whereas CD-2 combines with bacteria through hydrophobic interaction because it is weakly negatively charged. The accumulation of the two CDs on the surface of bacteria not only prevent the nutrient uptake by the cell from outside environment but also disrupt the bacterial membrane and increase the permeability of the cell membrane, which is beneficial for the entry of CDs into the cells and causes the leakage of bacterial contents. Moreover, both the CDs were less than 5 nm in size, which endows the quantum size effect and large specific surface area, making CDs strongly activite against bacteria and facilitating their entrance into bacteria. Gram-negative E. coli was chosen as the model to explore the effect of CDs on the surface morphology of bacteria through SEM observations. After incubation of E. coli with CD-2 (1 mg/mL) for 2 h, the surface of E. coli was in hollow, collapsed and severely damaged state, relative to the normally cultivated E. coli (Fig. 5
).
